{
  "local_port": 54020,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do you get good letters of recommendation?",
  "response": "Getting strong letters of recommendation requires careful planning, building relationships, and making the process as easy as possible for your recommender. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you secure good letters:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Choose the Right Recommenders**\n   - **Select people who know you well:** Choose individuals who can speak to your skills, achievements, and character in detail (e.g., professors, supervisors, mentors).\n   - **Relevance matters:** Pick recommenders who can speak to the qualities the program or job is looking for (e.g., academic ability, leadership, teamwork).\n   - **Avoid generic letters:** A letter from someone who doesn\u2019t know you well will lack depth and impact.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Build Strong Relationships**\n   - **Engage consistently:** Take the time to build genuine connections with potential recommenders. Participate in class, attend office hours, or volunteer for projects at work.\n   - **Show initiative:** Demonstrate your skills, work ethic, and commitment so they can write about specific examples.\n   - **Stay in touch:** If it\u2019s been a while since you\u2019ve worked with them, reconnect and remind them of your accomplishments together.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Ask Politely and Early**\n   - **Give ample notice:** Ask at least 3\u20134 weeks before the deadline to give them enough time to write a thoughtful letter.\n   - **Make it easy to say yes:** Approach them with gratitude and express why you value their opinion.\n   - **Provide an out:** Let them know it\u2019s okay to decline if they\u2019re too busy or don\u2019t feel comfortable writing the letter.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Provide Relevant Information**\n   - **Share your goals:** Explain why you\u2019re applying and what the letter is for (e.g., grad school, job, scholarship).\n   - **Highlight key points:** Provide a summary of your achievements, skills, and experiences they can reference.\n   - **Include materials:** Share your resume, personal statement, or a draft of your application to help them tailor the letter.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Guide Them on Content**\n   - **Suggest specific examples:** Remind them of projects, accomplishments, or qualities they can mention.\n   - **Provide guidelines:** Share any requirements (e.g., length, format) or prompts from the application.\n   - **Offer talking points:** Suggest areas they could focus on, such as your leadership, creativity, or problem-solving skills.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Follow Up Thoughtfully**\n   - **Send gentle reminders:** Politely check in a week or two before the deadline, especially if they haven\u2019t confirmed completion.\n   - **Express gratitude:** Thank them for their time and effort, whether or not you\u2019re accepted.\n   - **Keep them updated:** Share the outcome of your application to show appreciation for their support.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Write a Thank-You Note**\n   - After they submit the letter, send a handwritten note or email expressing your appreciation. Keep them informed about your progress and success.\n\n---\n\nBy being proactive, organized, and respectful, you can increase your chances of securing strong, personalized letters of recommendation that enhance your application.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
